TextBlock.TextLine: Amst De Hulter van Homright Antw: 8 9d 1683a
Mess. in antwoort aenden ul van 4 deser ben verwondert over mr. lune sjn
neglicentie, eghter tot uwe satisfactie sende hier ingesloten sijn ordre waerbij
hir commandeert de canten & de selve aen ul. toe te senden als mede mij
op ul te ram bourseeren hebbende sedert noch naeder ordre vanden selve bekomen
tot vermeerderinge van de pertije canten & het koopen van het stut selsoo
ul en kan dien volgens niet mitdoen aen mij de weerde te vergoede het tratsel
& packette kanten p eerst occasie on Dublen voot gaenckte geaen: de ratten
betlfacte boter is mij noch niet geworden soo die. eenighsins goet is salde
hooghste prijs traghte voor te bekomen wat de leijn rattiens belanght
heb daer over noch niet gesproken onderwijle heeft de versche & andere
rijt lansche boter voor eenige dagen voor in komende rechte dooor een perticu
ordinintie belast geweest, doch die is eghter aerstants afgedaen
soo dat de boter on belast is, hakende de wolle voor Andvan Roosendael afgelden
sal traghte tegens naest post dagh de spaensche merken te noteeren, als mede
wat wegens de sorte vant gesonden monster sal resolueeren alsoo myn
principaelste werckman uijtter stadt is eghter naer mijn deucke
soude daer vanderven ordannen, soo gelieft tot nast
postdagh eenigh tn bespirck tehouden want wel pertij sond
ordanen waer omen soo deselve daeren tiessen ni ge
verkoght worden soo behout 2 a 3 balen waermodl
Antwerpen 9 rb 1681
London Arthur Anneslay
h
S. in answer to yd of 26: past. have given you creditt for my halfe share
in the i5 serges aboard John Ewinghs from Exon, up on examination
of the patt. finde some of avere dull cullour yett god sending them safe
to arrive, shall endeavour to dispose off them to content, whilst alswor
do all I can to make you returnes as last as possible, for I could rather
wish to advance for you 2o then butt 6 a 8 pec., yett must have patience
as things now yo: I have accepted yd bill for £1501- for my acctt
& noted according to yd order whilst I remaine with kinde saluts
@ 9 ditto 1681
th
London William pinder
Sr. I have in due course recd. yd of 17: dune last & 27 past & according
to the first have accepted & payd yd bill of £40 att 36:1 which is according
past to acct att last have now sold yd. 6 resting serges so all is notwsted, butt
the mony not yett come in, towards which I do all possible endavour that
so I may remit you the ballance & send toghether the acct. of all, for I am as
desirous as you self to even that old bussynes, whower, I must tell you not to
draw on mee because when yd mony comes in itt shall be remitted withont
faile on which you may deien which Irest
@ 9 ditto 1681
London Eduind Warner
th
Sr. I have before mee yd of 22: past & returnee you thanckes for the
honour you gave my bill not doubting, butt that you forind all to contard
& that boath the packetts from Italy as wese as mine are come sale
to yd handes the letter beeng marched ES.WN.3 was att meuwporte
the 11: past according to what mr. vallego wrott mee, when I doubt
not butt itt is gott over att Dover where they are often ditained for
want of secure passage to london yett yd correspondent there ought
to anquunt you, as so one af the receaves any packetts as m. Vallugo
Doth to mee of their Receipt & sendny for ward att niespost in casoor
finde any in corrigment, or where in Elce I can serve you freey
command him that remaine with kinde salats
½ aus here are cheaper by 4 pec sence I send packett & likely
yett to continew so for some time haceing bought of lat
good parcell for freinds of lost
In Antwarp 9 sestember 81
London Will Scaven
th
Sr. I have before mee yd of 26: past. & returne you thanckes for paying mr. maynard
£109„ 670„ for the neat proceed of the 2 packetts of laces sent you, which I have
noted accordingly in yd creditt as for tykes they will not be cheaper this yeare, for
forne is to deare & wore much risen whoever I can afford y. you cheaper then
any other p and have att present about 150 peeces bj mee which in case you please
to have, shall assort them as you please to have y they beeng as by the inclosed
note you will see all chosen goods, and up on the word of an honest man I could
not have an other such parcell by 3 Pcc. so please not to delay yd answer
that in case you please not to have y. I may otherwise dispose of them as for
our Callicoes there are still about 1 so salempores with the dungarees dyed
insold besides 50 white & rawos brouwne, & other goods, so that I shall want
butt fews or non, except they were vere cheap, for in france is an Estundia
schip arrived & 8 inholand, from wheme they bring the goods so cheap here
that ours stand us in deaver here then I can buy them my self if the
browne long cloth of N.6 sells under 30 s you may provide 3 bales &
100 salempores to putt off the rest & no more which is allatt present I hiss
yd handes & so remaine I have here a parcell of good flax, pray a word
how that com. selss now with you
Sublin Elnathan Lumme
S. this Souert to the inclosed accompt for one packett of laces and a screen, which
are now in handes of the mess de Hulter & van Homrisht att amsterdam to come
forward with the first vessel butt still they write mee to have ns order from you
for seipping or doing mee good the valew, yett have ordered them to loose no opportunitie
in dieportching the same & that I should write for yd order to them of paying the
samce the valew: I will not doubt butt when you seen the lacces you will be
in corridged to in order more, for they are as cheap as ever laces were so that you mast
advance well by them, which I perceave by the continuall commissions I have from
london for that com. where in I can further serve you, you may assure yd self
that, yd commands shall be performed writh all lare & exactness imaginable that aw
London obram vivian
th
28 @ 10 ditto
Sr. my last to you was on the 3: curitt to which please to be referred sence recd yd of 26 past
with the bill of loading for 2 packes more aboard smith, god send him selfs overt
seeng the bayes could not come must exspect them by pindar, with the rest of the
bayes & other goods I shall in order no more for our winter provisions, butt exspect
out the time how sale will be besides, I tinckes when all what is in ordered
shall be here, that I shall be well assorted, except god did send us a better sale, then
as yett the time doth promises which comes most by the french continuall
pretentions & disturbands
I hape the rest of our goods will speedly be ready to
come with pindar & that I shall see you here suddamly: intrim the laces are ready & go
forward to marrow, butt forwant of time can not send you the invoyce now,
which you have to exspect p. next wilst with kinde saluts
@ 10 ditto
London Henry Collier
y
th
Sr. my last to you was on the 3: curitt sence rec. yd of 22 & 26 past part of the
cottons are sold & shall endeavour toe putt off the rest as well I can asalso the
gett resting goods, as for matters of trade beleave mee I have no comissions, butt from
you & ami not tyed to any boddy, butt which I finde doth best, thought I confees
I have some goods in comp. butt in case our trade doth continew to deercase as
this yeare hath don, am resolued to to ido more then what I shall be able to
compash with my owne for I finde I can hardely please these I serve yett
no endeavour in the least is wanting on my side to promote the intrest of
my freinds as well as mine, nay more where I can, where fore I am vere
sensible, that you would Re kone mee so indiscrett that I should have ammede
to beat you off from trade, which brought mee to itt nay though I should have
as great a stock againe, & beable to drive. my whole concernes for my acctt yettar
long as I liver shall endeavour to avoidall manners of imgrate fuslneer
to you butt ois a long you promised that then, on then you should have been in way
to leave off drawing & to spare mee as others do, so that I can not finde great
reasons why you should blame mee I have receaved never one fine cloathes butt
from you so that I have no goods of that sort to sell, butt for you & yett you ree
that Ihat no howfer you sended this yeare and still there are in all 17 of
yd cloathes msold, so that our sale is in considerable which in case dothmend
